"""
MKT Context Commentary — Proverbs chapter 31
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-proverbs-31-31.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/proverbs.json
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/proverbs.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Prov 31 is two distinct units: (1) vv1-9, the oracle of King Lemuel, a maternal
  wisdom instruction notable for its unusual female source in the patriarchal wisdom
  tradition; (2) vv10-31, the 'eshet hayil acrostic poem, 22 verses each beginning
  with a successive Hebrew letter (aleph to taw).
- "Lemuel" — an otherwise unknown royal name; ancient Jewish tradition identified him
  with Solomon, though this is uncertain. The name may be symbolic (le = "belonging
  to" + El = God). Some commentators read the poem as drawn from a non-Israelite
  wisdom tradition (the oracle form massa' appears in connection with Massa', a tribe
  of Ishmael in Gen 25:14).
- v21 "warm garments" — follows the qere reading of 'shanim' as "double/warm" rather
  than the kethib "scarlet"; both readings are defensible but "warm garments" fits
  the snow context better.
- v24 "Canaanite/merchant" — the word kena'ani (Canaanite) had acquired the secondary
  meaning of "merchant/trader" (cf. Zech 14:21) in later Hebrew usage; the MKT
  renders it as "traders" for clarity.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS = {
  "31": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 31 begins with a structurally anomalous header: <em>divrei Lemuel melekh</em> (words of King Lemuel) received as a <em>massa'</em> (oracle/burden) taught by his mother (<em>'asher yisserathu 'immo</em>). The wisdom tradition of Proverbs is overwhelmingly paternal in voice; this maternal voice is among only a handful in the Hebrew Bible (cf. the mother's instruction in Prov 1:8 and 6:20, where she is named alongside the father). The term <em>massa'</em> is used for prophetic oracle (Num 24:15; Isa 13:1; Hab 1:1) as well as for a place-name in Genesis 25:14 (a tribe of Ishmael), leading some scholars to read this as a non-Israelite wisdom tradition incorporated into the book. The identity of Lemuel remains uncertain; ancient tradition identified him with Solomon, but the name is otherwise unattested in the royal records.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The triple exclamation of <em>mah</em> (what?) — &ldquo;what, my son? What, son of my womb? What, son of my vows?&rdquo; — has been identified as an Aramaic rhetorical pattern (the Aramaic cognate of <em>mah</em> as an emphatic exclamation appears in Aramaic papyri). This suggests a possible non-Israelite or north-Syrian wisdom context for the oracle. The phrase <em>bar-nidarai</em> (son of my vows) echoes Hannah&rsquo;s dedicatory vow in 1 Samuel 1:11 (<em>ve-natati 'oto la-YHWH</em> — I will give him to YHWH). A son dedicated before birth to YHWH through a vow carries a particular obligation: his life is not merely his mother&rsquo;s son but YHWH&rsquo;s gift, which intensifies the responsibility to live well. The mother&rsquo;s instruction is therefore simultaneously maternal and covenantal.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The warning against giving &ldquo;strength to women&rdquo; (<em>et-chelecha la-nashim</em>) in the royal context reflects the political reality of the ancient Near Eastern harem system. Royal marriages were primarily diplomatic instruments: wives from client states or treaty partners sealed political alliances, and their maintenance was an ongoing obligation. Solomon&rsquo;s seven hundred wives and three hundred concubines (1 Kgs 11:3) represented a network of diplomatic commitments as much as personal relationships. The text specifically names these women as &ldquo;those who ruin kings&rdquo; (<em>ve-darakhekha la-mechot melakhim</em>) — the royal harem as the mechanism through which foreign cult obligations and political entanglements entered and destabilized the court. The Deuteronomic warning to the king (Deut 17:17 — &ldquo;he shall not acquire many wives&rdquo;) stands in the same tradition.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The prohibition of wine for kings and rulers (<em>lo' lemelakhim sheto-yayin</em>) reflects the ancient royal ideology that the king&rsquo;s primary function was judicial: the gate-court where he adjudicated disputes required clarity of mind that alcohol compromised. The wisdom literature of Egypt, Mesopotamia, and Israel consistently associates royal intoxication with judicial failure. The addressee <em>Lemuel</em> — explicitly identified as king — is being warned that the pleasure available to common citizens is not available to rulers, because the ruler&rsquo;s capacity belongs to the community and cannot be impaired. Leviticus 10:9 extends the same prohibition to priests: neither those who adjudicate (kings) nor those who offer (priests) may do so while impaired.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The specific danger of royal intoxication is the forgetting of <em>mehuqqaq</em> (what is decreed, the established law) and the perversion of justice (<em>yeshaneh din</em>) for the afflicted (<em>benei 'oni</em>, the sons of poverty/affliction). In the ancient Israelite legal system, the king was the court of final appeal for those who had been denied justice at the local level (cf. 2 Sam 15:1-6 where Absalom exploits the judicial backlog; 1 Kgs 3:16-28 where Solomon adjudicates the disputed child). The poor and afflicted had no other recourse than the king; if the king&rsquo;s judgment was corrupted by drink, the most vulnerable members of the community had no protection. The mother&rsquo;s instruction is therefore a social justice instruction dressed as personal advice to her son.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The counter-instruction — give strong drink to the perishing (<em>ten-shekhar le'oved</em>) and wine to those bitter of soul (<em>ule-mar nefesh yayin</em>) — reflects an ancient humane practice: alcohol as anesthetic for those beyond medical help. The practice of offering wine to condemned prisoners before execution is attested in several ANE contexts; Mark 15:23 records that wine mixed with myrrh was offered to Jesus before crucifixion. The <em>oved</em> (the perishing/dying one) and the <em>mar nefesh</em> (bitter of soul, the person in acute grief or terminal suffering) are identified as the appropriate recipients of the anesthetic use of wine that kings must decline for judicial reasons. The contrast sharpens both the prohibition (v4) and the compassionate use (v6): what is harmful for the judge is appropriate mercy for the sufferer.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The forgetting function of wine (<em>yishte ve-yishkach rishi</em>, he will drink and forget his poverty) is here treated as therapeutic rather than dangerous: for the person whose situation cannot be improved, forgetting is mercy. The word <em>rish</em> (H7389, poverty) in this context refers to the destitution that has become permanent — the person for whom economic recovery is no longer possible, perhaps through terminal illness, permanent disability, or enslavement. The <em>amal</em> (H5999, labor/toil/misery) that is remembered no more is the accumulated burden of a life of suffering. The proverb is not endorsing drunkenness as a life practice but identifying a specific compassionate use for what would otherwise be a social harm.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The command to &ldquo;open your mouth for the mute&rdquo; (<em>petch picha le'illem</em>) addresses the king&rsquo;s advocacy function in the gate-court. The <em>'illem</em> (the mute, H483, one who cannot speak) in the legal context refers not merely to those who are physically unable to speak but to those who have no access to advocacy: the widow without a male kinsman-redeemer, the orphan without a father to represent their case, the immigrant without community ties. Deuteronomy 10:18 identifies YHWH as the one who &ldquo;executes justice for the fatherless and the widow&rdquo; — the king was expected to embody this divine advocacy in the human court. The phrase <em>benei chalof</em> (sons of the passing-away, those left desolate) captures this social vulnerability: those who are socially alone, without advocates.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The doubled imperative — &ldquo;open your mouth, judge righteously&rdquo; (<em>petch-picha shephet-tzedeq</em>) — applies the judicial vocabulary of <em>mishpat</em> (just judgment) and <em>tzedeq</em> (righteousness) to the specific recipients: the poor (<em>'ani</em>) and needy (<em>'evyon</em>). Both terms are the standard vocabulary for the economically marginal in the Hebrew Bible — those who had lost their land, their family support, or their social standing. The mother&rsquo;s instruction closes its advocacy section with this positive command: the king who has disciplined himself in the areas of women and wine is not freed from all obligation but commissioned for service to the weakest members of the community. Self-discipline is instrumental to social justice.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The <em>'eshet chayil</em> (excellent/capable wife, literally &ldquo;woman of valor&rdquo;) poem begins here and continues to v31 in an alphabetic acrostic: each verse begins with a successive letter of the Hebrew alphabet from aleph (v10) to taw (v31). The acrostic form is a device of completeness (the alphabet from first to last letter = exhaustive coverage, as in Psalm 119 and Lamentations 1–4). The poem is presenting the complete picture of feminine virtue rather than a selective portrait. <em>Chayil</em> (H2428, valor/strength/army) is primarily a military and economic-strength term; its application to the household woman elevates domestic management to the same level of demanding excellence as the military or governance domains. The rhetorical question &ldquo;who can find her?&rdquo; (<em>mi yimtza'</em>) is not pessimism but the form of the quest-praise — the one who finds such a person has found something as rare and valuable as rubies (<em>peninim</em>, H6443, precious stones).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The husband&rsquo;s heart trusting in her (<em>vatach bah lev ba'alah</em>) uses the <em>batach</em> vocabulary (H982, to trust/rely on with confidence) — the same word used for trust in YHWH in the Psalms and wisdom literature. The depth of trust implied is not mere social confidence but the kind of reliance on another person that characterizes the human-divine relationship at its most fundamental. The result: <em>ve-shalal lo' yechsar</em> (he will lack no good thing, literally &ldquo;plunder he will not lack&rdquo;) — <em>shalal</em> (H7998, plunder/spoil/gain) applied to household prosperity uses the military vocabulary of gain; the husband&rsquo;s household prosperity flows from this trustworthy partnership.</p>",
    "12": "<p>She does him good and not evil (<em>gemalatthu tov ve-lo' ra'</em>) all the days of her life introduces the <em>gamal</em> vocabulary (H1580, to deal with/to benefit, the primary verb of covenant action). The same word is used for YHWH&rsquo;s dealings with Israel (<em>ki-gamal YHWH 'alayikh</em>, for YHWH has dealt bountifully with you, Ps 13:6). Her treatment of her husband is modeled on the covenant loyalty that YHWH shows to Israel: unbroken good through the entirety of her life. This frames the marriage relationship as a covenantal analog to the human-divine relationship — not merely a functional partnership but a loyalty commitment that mirrors YHWH&rsquo;s own faithfulness.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Seeking out wool and flax (<em>darshah tzemer ufishtim</em>) describes the raw-material procurement phase of the ancient household textile industry. Wool came from the household&rsquo;s own or neighbor&rsquo;s flocks; flax (linen fiber) was grown in fields and required processing (retting, drying, beating) before spinning. The textile industry was the primary economic activity of Israelite women: spinning, weaving, dyeing, and finishing cloth for household use and for sale. The verb <em>darshah</em> (to seek out, to investigate carefully, H1875) implies deliberate, thoughtful procurement — not passive acceptance of what is available but active acquisition of the best materials. <em>Ta'as be-chefetz kappeha</em> (she works willingly with her hands, literally &ldquo;she works with the delight/pleasure of her palms&rdquo;) characterizes the labor as motivated rather than compelled.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The merchant ships comparison (<em>hayetah ke'oniyyot socher</em>, she is like the ships of the merchant) elevates the 'eshet chayil&rsquo;s provisioning activities to the level of international maritime trade. The <em>oniyyot socher</em> (merchant ships, trading vessels) that brought goods from great distances (<em>mimerchaq tassi' lachma</em>, from far away she brings her bread/food) were the long-distance economy&rsquo;s most ambitious commercial vehicles. To compare the household manager&rsquo;s food provisioning to maritime trade is to honor it with the highest available image of commercial reach and ambition. This is not hyperbole but an argument: what she does for her household is as significant an act of commerce and provision as what the merchant fleet does for the wider economy.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Rising while it is still dark (<em>va-taqam be'od lailah</em>, she rises while it is yet night) and providing food for the household and assignments for servant girls (<em>na'aroteyha</em>) reflects the disciplined governance of a substantial household. The pre-dawn rise is associated in the wisdom and prophetic tradition with the servant of YHWH: Isaiah 50:4 uses the same image for the Servant who &ldquo;morning by morning&rdquo; receives and transmits the word. The assignment of tasks to servant girls (<em>vatiten tereph le-veitah ve-choq le-na'aroteha</em>) — the management of delegated labor — reflects the organizational complexity of the larger Israelite household where servants were a normal part of the domestic economy. The word <em>choq</em> (H2706, portion/statutory allotment) indicates she assigns measured tasks, not arbitrary demands.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Evaluating a field and buying it (<em>zammah sadeh va-tiqqachehu</em>, she considered a field and took it) describes property acquisition requiring financial assessment, market knowledge, and capital. In ancient Israel, land was the primary productive and inheritable asset; its purchase was a significant legal and economic transaction involving the elders at the gate (cf. the Boaz-kinsman land transaction in Ruth 4). The 'eshet chayil&rsquo;s ability to evaluate and acquire land independently reflects substantial economic agency within the patriarchal system. She then plants a vineyard (<em>mi-peri khappeha nate'ah karem</em>, from the fruit of her hands she plants a vineyard) — turning the field into long-term productive capital. The vineyard requires years to mature; she invests in the long-term household economy, not merely immediate provision.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Girding herself with strength (<em>chagrah ve'oz motneyha</em>, she has girded her loins with strength) uses the military dress vocabulary: girding the loins is the preparation of the soldier or traveler for strenuous action (cf. 1 Kgs 18:46; Isa 5:27; Luke 12:35). The image deliberately applies the warrior&rsquo;s preparation to the household woman&rsquo;s daily work, framing domestic labor as requiring the same kind of disciplined, full-body engagement as military service. <em>Va-te'ammetz zero'oteha</em> (she makes her arms strong, she strengthens her arms) uses the same verb (<em>'amatz</em>, H553) used for Joshua&rsquo;s commission — &ldquo;be strong and courageous&rdquo; — applied to the physical strength developed through consistent, demanding work.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Seeing that her trade is profitable (<em>ta'amah ki-tov sachrah</em>, she tastes that her trade is good) uses the tasting metaphor for tested experience: <em>ta'amah</em> (to taste, to perceive by experience, H2938) implies that she has assessed her commercial activities with the kind of direct, experience-based evaluation that the wisdom tradition commends. <em>Lo'-yichbeh ba-lailah nerah</em> (her lamp does not go out at night) is both a practical observation (she works into the night) and a theological symbol: the lamp that does not go out is a symbol of life and continuity in the Hebrew Bible (cf. Jer 25:10 where the extinguished lamp marks desolation). The household where the lamp burns through the night is the household of sustained life and activity.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The distaff (<em>kiyor</em>) and spindle (<em>pelek</em>) are the two fundamental implements of ancient textile production. The distaff was a stick or cleft around which the raw fiber (wool or flax) was wound; the spindle was the weighted shaft that drew out and twisted the fiber into thread through controlled rotation. This was the foundation of the household textile economy: all cloth began with the spinning of raw fiber into thread. The prominence of spinning in the poem (v13 wool and flax, v19 distaff and spindle, v22 fine linen, v24 linen garments) reflects the centrality of textile production to the household economy — not mere household crafting but the primary product of commercial value that the household produced and sold.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The immediately following verse (after the hands-at-spindle image of v19) opens her hands to the poor (<em>kapah paresah le'ani</em>) and extends them to the needy (<em>ve-yadeha shillechah la'evyon</em>). The structural placement — v19 hands at productive work, v20 same hands opened to the poor — makes generosity the direct continuation of productivity rather than a separate virtue. In the ancient household economy, surplus from production went either toward re-investment (v16 vineyard purchase) or charitable distribution (v20). The wisdom tradition holds these in balance: the industrious person creates the surplus that makes generosity possible; generosity is the social obligation that productive abundance incurs. The two hands of v20 (<em>kapah</em> and <em>yadeha</em>) are the same hands as v19, now redirected.</p>",
    "21": "<p>No fear of snow for the household (<em>lo' tira' le-veitah mishaleig</em>) reflects the Palestinian climate where late-winter snow could fall in the highlands (Jerusalem, Bethlehem, Hebron) creating fuel and clothing shortages. <em>Ki chol-beitah lavush shanim</em> — all her household are clothed in <em>shanim</em>. The reading of <em>shanim</em> follows a textual ambiguity: the Masoretic text could be read as &ldquo;scarlet&rdquo; (H8145, crimson dye, the expensive color of prestige textiles) or as &ldquo;double garments&rdquo; (from <em>shanah</em>, to double/repeat). The context of protection from snow makes the double/warm reading more functional, though the scarlet reading would emphasize the household&rsquo;s prosperity and her pride in her family&rsquo;s appearance. Both readings reflect her advance provision.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The fine linen (<em>shesh</em>) and purple (<em>'argaman</em>) of her own clothing are the luxury textile combination worn by the Israelite priesthood (Exod 28:5-6), by royalty (1 Chr 15:27; Esth 8:15), and by the wealthy. <em>Shesh</em> is the Egyptian fine linen used in the tabernacle (Exod 26:1); <em>'argaman</em> is Phoenician purple dye made from the murex shellfish, one of the most expensive colorants in the ancient world. By wearing fine linen and purple, the 'eshet chayil does not merely reflect her own excellence as a textile producer (she can produce the finest cloth) but also her household&rsquo;s economic standing — the same cloth that adorns priests and kings adorns the woman who manages her household as its household-priestess and domestic ruler.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The husband known in the gates among the elders (<em>noda' bashearim ba'alah beshivto im-ziqnei-'aretz</em>) makes explicit the social connection between the wife&rsquo;s domestic management and the husband&rsquo;s public standing. The gate (<em>sha'ar</em>) was the physical-social location of civic life in the ancient Israelite city: contracts were witnessed, disputes adjudicated, commercial transactions recorded, and community decisions made at the gate by the assembled elders (<em>ziqnei-'aretz</em>, elders of the land). The husband&rsquo;s ability to sit among these elders and be recognized as a man of standing (<em>noda'</em>, known/distinguished) depends partly on the household economy his wife manages: his public authority is partially built on the private competence she exercises.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Making and selling linen garments (<em>sadin asethah va-timkor</em>) and supplying sashes (<em>chagor</em>) to merchants (<em>la-kena'ani natetah</em>, to the Canaanite/trader she gives) describes the commercial extension of the household textile industry into the marketplace. The word <em>kena'ani</em> (Canaanite) had acquired the secondary meaning of &ldquo;merchant/trader&rdquo; in biblical Hebrew (cf. Job 40:30; Zech 14:21) — Canaanites were stereotypically associated with commerce in the ancient Near East. The 'eshet chayil sells both finished garments (<em>sadin</em>, fine linen) and accessories (<em>chagor</em>, belt/sash) to professional traders, meaning her production extends beyond household use to commercial scale. She is simultaneously a manufacturer and wholesaler.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Strength and honor as her clothing (<em>'oz ve-hadar levushah</em>) inverts the ordinary clothing metaphor: where v22 described her literal clothing, here her character-qualities (<em>'oz</em>, strength; <em>hadar</em>, dignity/splendor) are named as her garments. <em>Hadar</em> (H1926, honor/glory/splendor) is used for the glory of YHWH (Ps 8:2; 104:1) and for the dignity of age and accomplishment. <em>Va-tischaq le-yom 'acharon</em> (she laughs at the day to come, literally &ldquo;she laughs at the last day&rdquo;) is the expression of eschatological confidence: she looks toward the future without anxiety because her preparations are complete and her character is established. The laughter of the wise at the future is not frivolity but the serenity of the one who has nothing to fear.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Opening her mouth with wisdom (<em>picha patetah be-chokmah</em>) and having the <em>torat chesed</em> (instruction of covenant-loyalty) on her tongue places her speech firmly within the wisdom-covenant tradition of the book. <em>Torah</em> in this phrase is not the Mosaic Torah but instruction/teaching (<em>torah</em> from <em>yarah</em>, to teach) — the guidance she gives to her household, servants, and potentially others. <em>Chesed</em> (H2617, covenant loyalty, loving-kindness) as the quality that characterizes her teaching goes beyond mere accuracy or wisdom: she teaches in a way that reflects the covenant faithfulness of YHWH toward Israel. The phrase <em>torat chesed</em> is unique in the Hebrew Bible — the fusion of instruction and covenant loyalty is the poem&rsquo;s highest praise of her speech.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Watching over the affairs of her household (<em>tzofiyyah halikot beitah</em>, she watches over the walkings/goings of her household) uses the <em>tzafah</em> vocabulary (H6822, to look out, to watch as a sentinel) applied to household management. The sentinel&rsquo;s function — vigilant observation from an elevated position to warn of approaching danger — is applied to the 'eshet chayil&rsquo;s managerial oversight of the household economy. The phrase <em>lechem 'atzlut lo' tochel</em> (she does not eat the bread of idleness) inverts the bread-of-idleness idiom: bread earned through idleness is the opposite of bread earned through productive work. Her refusal of the bread of idleness connects her to the ant of Proverbs 6:6-8 — the model of productive diligence that does not wait for external compulsion.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Her children rising to call her blessed (<em>qamu vaneha va-ye'ashruha</em>) and her husband praising her (<em>ba'alah va-yehallalah</em>) describes the household honor ceremony — the public recognition of excellence within the domestic sphere. The word <em>'ashar</em> (H833, to pronounce blessed/happy) is the word of the beatitude — the same root as the Psalter&rsquo;s <em>'ashrei</em> (blessed/happy is the person who...). Her children&rsquo;s rising (<em>qamu</em>, they stand up for her) is the posture of honor-recognition in ancient cultures: one stood for persons of superior standing. The husband&rsquo;s praise (<em>yehallel</em>, the same root as <em>hallelujah</em>, to praise extravagantly) is the domestic parallel to the public praise she receives in v31.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The husband&rsquo;s direct speech of praise — &ldquo;many women have done excellently, but you surpass them all&rdquo; (<em>rabbot banot 'asu-chayil ve'at 'alit 'al-kullanah</em>) — uses the superlative of the <em>chayil</em> vocabulary that has defined the poem from v10. The <em>'alit</em> (you have risen above/surpassed) positions her above all others in the category of valor-excellence. The comparison with &ldquo;many women&rdquo; (<em>rabbot banot</em>) places the poem in a context of comparative evaluation: the poem is not claiming that all women are like this but that this woman surpasses those who are themselves excellent. The logic of the praise is ascending excellence, not exclusive status.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The theological climax of the poem and the book: <em>yir'at YHWH hi' tithhallal</em> — a woman who fears the LORD is to be praised. The two negative contrasts set the frame: <em>sheger ha-chen</em> (charm is deception/vanity, H8267) and <em>hevel ha-yofi</em> (beauty is breath/vanity, H1892 — the same word as Ecclesiastes&rsquo; <em>hevel</em>, vapor/emptiness). Both of the qualities that ancient and modern cultures have most consistently evaluated women by — charm and physical beauty — are dismissed as <em>sheger</em> and <em>hevel</em>: the one is actively deceptive, the other is insubstantial vapor. The fear of the LORD (<em>yir'at YHWH</em>) is the quality that the entire book of Proverbs has identified as the beginning of wisdom (1:7) and its conclusion (9:10). The poem ends by anchoring the 'eshet chayil&rsquo;s excellence not in her social performance or productivity but in her orientation to YHWH — she is most fundamentally a person who fears God.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The concluding verse — &ldquo;give her the fruit of her hands, and let her works praise her in the gates&rdquo; — closes the poem with a call to honor that is public (<em>bishearim</em>, in the gates) and productivity-based (<em>peri yadeha</em>, the fruit of her hands; <em>ma'aseyha</em>, her works). The gates where her husband sat among elders (v23) are the same gates where her works now testify on her behalf. She needs no advocate: her commercial production, charitable practice, household management, and wisdom-teaching are themselves her witnesses in the public-judicial space of the ancient community. The poem that began with &ldquo;who can find her?&rdquo; (v10) ends with her works making her findable and recognizable in the most public space available. The book of Proverbs, which opened with a father&rsquo;s instruction in wisdom, closes with the portrait of wisdom embodied in a woman whose life is its own argument.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(existing, PROVERBS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in PROVERBS.values())
    print(f'Proverbs 31 mkt-context: {total} verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
